            <p rend="align(center)">TO THE PUBLIC</p>
            <p rend="align(center)">THE OCCIDENT,</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">The oldest Jewish periodical in the English language, has finished its<lb/>
                <hi rend="italics">twenty-fifth</hi> volume. Under the able editorship of the late
                    <persName>Rev. Isaac<lb/> Leeser</persName>, it has become a renowned champion
                of Judaism, and a successful<lb/> promoter of Jewish literature. It was his earnest
                wish that its publication<lb/> should be continued after his death. Personally, and
                in his will, he requested<lb/> the subscriber to take editorial charge of it, and
                although there were many<lb/> reasons to cause hesitancy in accepting the trust, two
                circumstances over-<lb/>came his reluctance. The one was a natural anxiety that the
                desire of his<lb/> lamented friend should be fulfilled, and the other, a conviction
                that the Jews<lb/> of <placeName>America</placeName> still need an organ which has
                so long maintained its position.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Its literary character will be such as to make it attractive to all
                households,<lb/> and neither pains nor expense will be spared to procure
                contributions on<lb/> Jewish subjects from persons of talent.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Its religious position is too well defined to need any explanation.
                In the<lb/> words of <persName>Mr. Leeser</persName>, “Whatever can promote the
                welfare of Israelites and<lb/> their faith, shall always find an ardent advocate in
                it; whatever is hostile to<lb/> either, shall ever meet its decided opposition.”</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">To Jewish families, everywhere, who desire to know the events
                which<lb/> affect their co-religionists in all parts of the world, this work will be
                a wel-<lb/>come visitor. Hebrew scholars will find its pages enriched with many
                arti-<lb/>cles instructive even to the learned, and the public generally will
                receive<lb/> from it information of a character elsewhere unattainable.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">The great and increasing importance of the numerous and influential
                order<lb/> of B'nai Berith, will be recognized, by the creation of a B. B.
                department in<lb/> this magazine.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">It appears in monthly parts of at least forty-eight pages octavo,
                forming,<lb/> at the end of the year, a handsome volume. The price is <hi
                    rend="italics">Four</hi> Dollars per<lb/> annum, in advance.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Advertisements will be inserted on the cover at the rate of 25 cents
                per<lb/> line, for the first insertion; every subsequent one will be charged 20
                cents.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Annual cards and school advertisements inserted on special
                agreement.<lb/> Nothing inserted for less <sic>shan</sic>
                <hi rend="italics">One</hi> Dollar.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Obituaries, resolutions, and complimentary notice of any kind, 30
                cents<lb/> per line; marriage notices $1 each.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">The wide circulation of the <hi rend="italics">Occident</hi> among
                the Jews, not only in this city<lb/> and country, but also in foreign lands, makes
                it an excellent vehicle for<lb/> advertisements intended to meet their eyes.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Liberal inducements will be offered to all who are willing to act as
                our<lb/> agents, and to clubs.</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Address, <persName role="author">MAYER SULZBERGER</persName>,
                EDITOR</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">29 <hi rend="italics"><placeName>South Sixth St.,
                        Philadelphia</placeName>.</hi></p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <hi rend="bold">SUBSCRIBERS' NAMES. RESIDENCE.</hi>
            </p>
